WEBVTT

00:00:01.040 --> 00:00:04.480
So far in our journey through deep

00:00:02.879 --> 00:00:08.000
learning,

00:00:04.480 --> 00:00:10.639
we started with multi-layer perceptrons

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:15.719
that took our emnest images, flattened

00:00:10.639 --> 00:00:15.719
them into a long vector of 784,

00:00:15.759 --> 00:00:21.039
fed them into the input layer. And our

00:00:18.880 --> 00:00:24.080
model learned

00:00:21.039 --> 00:00:29.119
to classify them into one of the 10

00:00:24.080 --> 00:00:32.960
digits. It was always 784 neurons in and

00:00:29.119 --> 00:00:35.600
always 10 classes out a fixed rigid

00:00:32.960 --> 00:00:38.399
contract. Then we moved on to

00:00:35.600 --> 00:00:41.600
convolutional neural networks. The

00:00:38.399 --> 00:00:44.719
superstars of image recognition.

00:00:41.600 --> 00:00:47.600
We trained them on data sets like

00:00:44.719 --> 00:00:51.920
imageet where every input image was

00:00:47.600 --> 00:00:56.320
resized to a specific shape like 224x

00:00:51.920 --> 00:00:59.120
224 pixels to be classified into one of

00:00:56.320 --> 00:01:01.760
the 1,000 categories. Once again, the

00:00:59.120 --> 00:01:04.000
input and output sizes were always

00:01:01.760 --> 00:01:06.320
fixed. So there's a fundamental

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:10.000
constraint we've been working with up

00:01:06.320 --> 00:01:13.680
until now. These models demand that our

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:17.759
world fits into a neat fixedsiz box. An

00:01:13.680 --> 00:01:23.360
MLP needs exactly 784 features. A CNN

00:01:17.759 --> 00:01:26.080
needs exactly 224x 224 pixels. So what

00:01:23.360 --> 00:01:28.799
happens when our data doesn't cooperate?

00:01:26.080 --> 00:01:33.200
What if I want to process a fiveword

00:01:28.799 --> 00:01:36.159
sentence or analyze a 100word paragraph?

00:01:33.200 --> 00:01:39.360
Or what about classifying a 2-hour movie

00:01:36.159 --> 00:01:43.360
or a 15-minute short film? A standard

00:01:39.360 --> 00:01:46.159
CNN or MLP architectures simply cannot

00:01:43.360 --> 00:01:47.920
handle that. So the reality is most of

00:01:46.159 --> 00:01:51.040
the world's interesting data doesn't

00:01:47.920 --> 00:01:54.079
come in fixed sizes. Text can be a

00:01:51.040 --> 00:01:55.920
two-word phrase like hello there or an

00:01:54.079 --> 00:01:58.799
entire novel. This is the challenge

00:01:55.920 --> 00:02:02.799
ahead of us. We need to build a bridge

00:01:58.799 --> 00:02:05.200
from the fixed size world we know to the

00:02:02.799 --> 00:02:08.319
variable size world of real data. That

00:02:05.200 --> 00:02:10.800
brings us to our wall for today. We will

00:02:08.319 --> 00:02:14.000
learn a powerful framework that can

00:02:10.800 --> 00:02:17.040
handle inputs of any size. But for now,

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:19.680
we'll sidestep that a little bit uh with

00:02:17.040 --> 00:02:22.319
a clever trick. We will learn to

00:02:19.680 --> 00:02:25.599
compress them into a meaningful fixed

00:02:22.319 --> 00:02:27.840
size representation that allow us to

00:02:25.599 --> 00:02:30.879
return to the charted territory of fixed

00:02:27.840 --> 00:02:34.160
input models. But before jumping into

00:02:30.879 --> 00:02:35.840
complex tasks like machine translation

00:02:34.160 --> 00:02:39.040
uh where we dealing with different

00:02:35.840 --> 00:02:41.519
languages, variable length sequences and

00:02:39.040 --> 00:02:44.879
all sorts of uh complications. Let's

00:02:41.519 --> 00:02:48.800
start with a simple autoenccoders. Auto

00:02:44.879 --> 00:02:51.519
encoders introduce a um an architecture

00:02:48.800 --> 00:02:54.400
that we need without any really

00:02:51.519 --> 00:02:57.200
complexity of having different types of

00:02:54.400 --> 00:03:00.160
inputs and and outputs. The contract

00:02:57.200 --> 00:03:03.360
here the autoenccoded contract is very

00:03:00.160 --> 00:03:06.080
simple and the input X let's say of

00:03:03.360 --> 00:03:10.640
dimension D for now like I said we can

00:03:06.080 --> 00:03:14.959
have different size so one easy tree can

00:03:10.640 --> 00:03:18.000
be if X can take different size we just

00:03:14.959 --> 00:03:21.200
assume the largest possible size that X

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:25.840
can take and then we pad the rest of

00:03:21.200 --> 00:03:29.519
those empty um dimensions. Okay. So with

00:03:25.840 --> 00:03:32.879
that we have an input X and we encode

00:03:29.519 --> 00:03:35.599
this using an encoder let's call it

00:03:32.879 --> 00:03:37.599
encoder to another space uh latent

00:03:35.599 --> 00:03:40.560
space. The dimension of this latent

00:03:37.599 --> 00:03:43.599
space is much lower. And you can think

00:03:40.560 --> 00:03:48.480
of it like it is basically the the

00:03:43.599 --> 00:03:52.560
concept that X carries with itself.

00:03:48.480 --> 00:03:56.319
And usually this is much has a much

00:03:52.560 --> 00:03:58.480
lower dimension that uh X of course X

00:03:56.319 --> 00:04:02.239
has many paddings and like for example

00:03:58.480 --> 00:04:05.360
in t text we have punctuation marks and

00:04:02.239 --> 00:04:09.680
etc. But the real meaning that this

00:04:05.360 --> 00:04:12.879
piece of text is carrying is carry uh

00:04:09.680 --> 00:04:15.920
has much lower dimension. So that's why

00:04:12.879 --> 00:04:18.799
usually the encoder really compresses

00:04:15.920 --> 00:04:23.440
the data. So to to compute the loss

00:04:18.799 --> 00:04:26.960
often we have to either go to u label

00:04:23.440 --> 00:04:30.880
space or a space that is uh similar to

00:04:26.960 --> 00:04:32.639
the space of x. So in the simplest case,

00:04:30.880 --> 00:04:34.639
let's just assume that we want to

00:04:32.639 --> 00:04:37.520
compress the data and we want to

00:04:34.639 --> 00:04:40.479
reconstruct it, right? So we want to

00:04:37.520 --> 00:04:43.360
reconstruct X with the same dimension.

00:04:40.479 --> 00:04:48.320
So we want the decoder to send back the

00:04:43.360 --> 00:04:50.639
latent space Z to the original space X

00:04:48.320 --> 00:04:54.240
hat. So in this case what we are doing

00:04:50.639 --> 00:04:57.520
is basically we compress X to a latent

00:04:54.240 --> 00:05:01.199
space and then we want this compression

00:04:57.520 --> 00:05:04.240
to be in a way that we can retrieve X to

00:05:01.199 --> 00:05:06.479
the best of our ability. So how we can

00:05:04.240 --> 00:05:09.600
do it we basically want the

00:05:06.479 --> 00:05:12.479
reconstructed X to be very close to the

00:05:09.600 --> 00:05:14.160
to the original X. So some form of

00:05:12.479 --> 00:05:16.720
distance between these two that we want

00:05:14.160 --> 00:05:18.960
to minimize and this will be our loss of

00:05:16.720 --> 00:05:21.759
uh this autoenccoder. So this is much

00:05:18.960 --> 00:05:24.479
simpler than translation where we have

00:05:21.759 --> 00:05:28.240
um input X for example in English and

00:05:24.479 --> 00:05:31.120
the output in French which is a let's

00:05:28.240 --> 00:05:33.759
say a different space or for example the

00:05:31.120 --> 00:05:37.120
input can be images and the output can

00:05:33.759 --> 00:05:39.280
be captions right again different spaces

00:05:37.120 --> 00:05:42.240
so for now let's just focus on this

00:05:39.280 --> 00:05:44.960
simpler architecture a very simple goal

00:05:42.240 --> 00:05:48.880
we want to compress X in a way that we

00:05:44.960 --> 00:05:51.280
can retrieve most of the information in

00:05:48.880 --> 00:05:54.479
X later on. Believe it or not, you've

00:05:51.280 --> 00:05:57.919
been using this all along, but of course

00:05:54.479 --> 00:06:01.440
with a different disguise. Recall PCA

00:05:57.919 --> 00:06:05.039
principal component analysis. In PCA, we

00:06:01.440 --> 00:06:07.600
had a let's say D-dimensional input

00:06:05.039 --> 00:06:09.440
after centering uh so basically mean

00:06:07.600 --> 00:06:12.800
should be zero. We have some

00:06:09.440 --> 00:06:16.639
normalization here. So after doing that

00:06:12.800 --> 00:06:19.919
we encode or in other word in PCA we

00:06:16.639 --> 00:06:22.639
project the data into the top k

00:06:19.919 --> 00:06:25.840
principal components. So mathematically

00:06:22.639 --> 00:06:28.960
this was where v was the matrix of

00:06:25.840 --> 00:06:33.039
principal component vectors right and z

00:06:28.960 --> 00:06:36.000
was the compressed code uh that was in k

00:06:33.039 --> 00:06:38.960
dimension because of the k principal

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:41.440
components. So basically if you remember

00:06:38.960 --> 00:06:44.240
when we visualized that it was like a

00:06:41.440 --> 00:06:47.120
rotation that finds the the most

00:06:44.240 --> 00:06:49.600
variation in X. So for example if your X

00:06:47.120 --> 00:06:52.560
was like this and you had two

00:06:49.600 --> 00:06:56.080
dimensional data it was enough to find

00:06:52.560 --> 00:06:59.840
this PC which is now one dimension.

00:06:56.080 --> 00:07:04.400
Okay. So how we can decode this? We

00:06:59.840 --> 00:07:08.080
basically send this back to the original

00:07:04.400 --> 00:07:10.800
coordinate which can be done by the same

00:07:08.080 --> 00:07:12.800
rotation but the inverse right and here

00:07:10.800 --> 00:07:16.240
since it's a rotation matrix inverse is

00:07:12.800 --> 00:07:19.599
just a transpose. So PCA is simply

00:07:16.240 --> 00:07:21.680
finding the best possible linear encoder

00:07:19.599 --> 00:07:25.120
and decoder to minimize the

00:07:21.680 --> 00:07:27.280
reconstruction error. PCA works because

00:07:25.120 --> 00:07:29.599
compression works. The idea of

00:07:27.280 --> 00:07:31.759
compressing data through this smaller

00:07:29.599 --> 00:07:33.599
representation leads to a core concept

00:07:31.759 --> 00:07:36.080
in deep learning the information

00:07:33.599 --> 00:07:42.400
bottleneck. So in the case of amnest for

00:07:36.080 --> 00:07:46.160
example we had this 78 784 dimension and

00:07:42.400 --> 00:07:48.240
we encode this to for example let's say

00:07:46.160 --> 00:07:53.199
32dimensional

00:07:48.240 --> 00:07:56.879
um latent space which is much smaller

00:07:53.199 --> 00:08:00.160
and then we could reconstruct the data

00:07:56.879 --> 00:08:04.479
with maybe some blur but to some to most

00:08:00.160 --> 00:08:07.599
of extent it's the same same image.

00:08:04.479 --> 00:08:10.560
And this shows this information

00:08:07.599 --> 00:08:13.680
bottleneck that we are talking about. In

00:08:10.560 --> 00:08:16.160
other words, we don't want the model to

00:08:13.680 --> 00:08:18.800
memorize everything, right? We want the

00:08:16.160 --> 00:08:22.080
model to learn the patterns and there

00:08:18.800 --> 00:08:24.240
are not really a lot of pattern here as

00:08:22.080 --> 00:08:27.680
many as the pixel. So, we don't need to

00:08:24.240 --> 00:08:30.240
really memorize the pixel. Instead we

00:08:27.680 --> 00:08:34.000
learn the patterns which are much lower

00:08:30.240 --> 00:08:37.760
dimension than that original pixels.

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:39.760
This way we enforce the model to learn

00:08:37.760 --> 00:08:42.080
an abstraction

00:08:39.760 --> 00:08:45.120
remove noises

00:08:42.080 --> 00:08:50.160
and find structures. So I I encourage

00:08:45.120 --> 00:08:54.080
you to review these PCA and how there we

00:08:50.160 --> 00:08:58.399
find this vectors and through minimizing

00:08:54.080 --> 00:09:02.080
the MSE loss. Basically we want to

00:08:58.399 --> 00:09:04.959
minimize an MSSE loss like this.

00:09:02.080 --> 00:09:06.720
Note that there is no bias term here in

00:09:04.959 --> 00:09:10.560
this

00:09:06.720 --> 00:09:14.959
uh linear

00:09:10.560 --> 00:09:16.480
uh translations or rotation just like a

00:09:14.959 --> 00:09:19.120
linear

00:09:16.480 --> 00:09:22.000
feed forward neural network without

00:09:19.120 --> 00:09:24.240
activation. So you could just similar to

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:28.080
what we did in linear regression. Of

00:09:24.240 --> 00:09:31.920
course no bias. We have one linear layer

00:09:28.080 --> 00:09:37.040
and another linear layer. So what if we

00:09:31.920 --> 00:09:41.120
insert just like what we did for uh MLP

00:09:37.040 --> 00:09:43.519
we can insert nonlinearity in this feed

00:09:41.120 --> 00:09:46.000
forward neural network right so like I

00:09:43.519 --> 00:09:49.760
said in PCA

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:53.760
we have one linear neural network and

00:09:49.760 --> 00:09:57.680
another one here again linear what if we

00:09:53.760 --> 00:10:00.720
add nonlinearity just like before and

00:09:57.680 --> 00:10:02.959
add more layers so in This case, the

00:10:00.720 --> 00:10:05.600
model is no longer restricted to

00:10:02.959 --> 00:10:08.640
learning flat spaces. We've learned this

00:10:05.600 --> 00:10:13.040
before. It can now learn to represent

00:10:08.640 --> 00:10:16.560
data lying on complex curved manifolds,

00:10:13.040 --> 00:10:19.680
not just linear spaces, but very complex

00:10:16.560 --> 00:10:22.000
geometries. PCA cannot do that. But we

00:10:19.680 --> 00:10:25.040
can do it. We know how to do it. We call

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:28.240
this an autoenccoder. Basically, a PCA

00:10:25.040 --> 00:10:32.880
on a steroid. Right? So now we have

00:10:28.240 --> 00:10:35.519
multiple layers with nonlinearity

00:10:32.880 --> 00:10:38.880
and we do the same thing still we do

00:10:35.519 --> 00:10:42.399
reconstruction still we want x and x hat

00:10:38.880 --> 00:10:45.920
to be close to each other but this way

00:10:42.399 --> 00:10:49.360
we basically find a representation of x

00:10:45.920 --> 00:10:51.920
that is much richer and possibly even in

00:10:49.360 --> 00:10:54.480
much less dimension because now we have

00:10:51.920 --> 00:10:57.360
richer representation. So maybe instead

00:10:54.480 --> 00:11:00.399
of 32, we could do much less for amnes.

00:10:57.360 --> 00:11:03.200
Let's say 10 for example. Okay. So this

00:11:00.399 --> 00:11:04.959
is basically a standard autoenccoder

00:11:03.200 --> 00:11:07.519
that does the reconstruction. But we

00:11:04.959 --> 00:11:11.120
could do more, right? We can we could

00:11:07.519 --> 00:11:15.120
basically have an X and inject noise. So

00:11:11.120 --> 00:11:19.360
a noisy X and we do the same

00:11:15.120 --> 00:11:22.240
architecture, but we demand a clean X.

00:11:19.360 --> 00:11:23.920
Okay. So this way we learn to clean the

